Barack Obama will be the fourth US president to receive the Nobel Peace Prize.
U.S. President Barack Obama will fly to Oslo for 26 hours to be the fourth U.S. president to receive the Nobel Peace Prize.
He will receive a diploma, medal and check for $1.4 million, among other things, for his exceptional efforts to strengthen world diplomacy and cooperation between nations.
The head of the White House will arrive in the Norwegian capital in the morning with his wife Michelle and will be busy.
He will first visit the Nobel Institute, where he will meet for the first time with five members of the committee, which in October selected him from 172 people and 33 organizations.
The presidential couple then have a scheduled meeting with King Harald V of Norway and Queen Sonja.
In the afternoon, the visit will culminate in a ceremony at which Obama will receive a prestigious award.
He will be the fourth U.S. president to win the award, but only the third to win it in office.
The White House has already announced that Obama will talk about the Afghan war when accepting the award.
The president does not want to avoid this topic because he realizes that he is taking over the award as a president who is currently at war in two countries.
The war effort a few days ago increased even more by sending more troops to Afghanistan, which will not forget to highlight any of its critics.
At the ceremony, Obama will also receive a gold medal, a diploma and a check for ten million Swedish kronor (about 24 million Czech crowns).
He's going to give it to charity, but he hasn't decided on a particular charity yet.
A packed program will take the president and his wife to a banquet where, in addition to the Norwegian king and queen, there will also be a prime minister and 250 other invited guests.
Obama has been reluctant from the start.
He said, for example, that he felt that he did not fully deserve it.
He also reiterated several times that the prize is not just for him, but for all those who strive for the same values as him.
Immediately after the announcement, he said it was a "call to action" for him.
