Repetition is the Mother of Wisdom
It is comical how Barack Obama, the president with the reputation of being the smartest, repeats in the Afghan question the strategy of his predecessor, whom he himself considered the dumbest.
When he finally sweated out his eagerly awaited Afghan doctrine, it turned out that he had copied it through a copier from Bush’s Iraq script three years ago.
Not only does he use the phrase "as in Iraq" several times in the text itself, but he did not even hesitate to use the title of Bush's January 2007 statement as the title of his own declaration: "A New Way Forward".
Three years ago, he criticized Bush’s idea to send fresh military reinforcements to Iraq, which was plagued by civil war, as “irresponsible and a catastrophic decision in its aftermath.”
However, the months that followed showed that Bush’s strategy, based on the recommendations of field commanders, was the only one possible and so successful that the news reports today do not talk about Iraq at all.
It didn’t improve Bush’s reputation, but objectively left his successor a much more grateful starting point than might have been expected.
In Afghanistan, Barack Obama hopes that the miracle will happen again.
He was once again asked to increase the military contingent by field commanders, especially the commander-in-chief of the Afghan operation, General Stanley McCristal, who even despite the subordination practices harshly criticized the hesitant shooters in the White House.
He asked 40,000 men to break the situation for the better.
The president hesitated for three months, but nothing better came of it, so at least he defrauded the general of 10,000 soldiers.
From Europe he managed to squeeze out the promise of another 5,000, although he originally counted at least 10.
The most problematic of Obama’s entire strategy seems to be his intention to start withdrawing troops from Afghanistan in just 18 months and to end the process in three years. The whole Obama doctrine raises more questions than it provides answers.
Many doubt that a half-increase will bear the same fruit as the procedure in Iraq.
Despite the fratricidal wars of recent years, Iraqi society is relatively well-ordered, its leaders honoring the agreement.
The Afghan situation is marked by the opposite symptom - no one can be relied on and no agreements are respected.
Under these conditions, Afghan security forces, accustomed to changing their masters on a daily basis, are poorly prepared.
Political institutions, even if formally established, will remain only a potemkin village, for which patriarchal tribal relations will continue to thrive.
Balancing the interests of different ethnic groups is extremely difficult due to the opacity of the situation, which further complicates Pakistani and Iranian influences.
Even the construction of an "accessible state", which is the minimalist goal of the whole operation, does not seem to be very real.
The time horizon of Obama’s strategy is striking with its voluntarism.
Over the past eight years, the situation in Afghanistan has only worsened and is now on the verge of exploding.
Believing that the soldiers sent into the turmoil of war for the purpose of "early return home" will cause a miracle here, can only a truly romantic soul, untouched by reality.
From a political point of view, setting a date for troop withdrawal is sheer irresponsibility, as the Taliban will see this as an indirect admission of American defeat.
The last NATO summit showed that the willingness of Europeans to participate in combat operations in Afghanistan is going to a minus.
European politicians cannot and do not want to explain to their voters how the security of Germany or Italy is related to the war in the foothills of the Hindu Kush.
Another factor capable of radically interfering in the situation is the development of events around Iran.
If the situation continues to deteriorate and the increased sanctions do not affect the Iranians, there will be a difficult question for the United States whether or not to try to solve the problem by military force.
It will have to be answered at a time when, according to Obama, America will proceed to a victorious withdrawal from Afghanistan.
However, any such solution will also mean a dramatic turnaround in the Afghan situation.
The only patch for Barack Obama is the fact that there are three years until the presidential election, and therefore enough time to come up with another strategy if it turns out to be a total flop.
