Czech discovery: a substance that works even on 'tough' HIV viruses
A team of Czech and German scientists is testing new compounds that can slow the spread of HIV in the body.
The main advantage of the improved substance is that it also works on viruses that have already gained immunity against drugs.
This fact in some cases outweighs the fact that the compound on the common variant of the virus does not act as strongly as some already available drugs.
AIDS is not yet curable.
However, patients can significantly prolong the life of a mixture of drugs that prevent the multiplication of the HIV virus in the body.
However, their use is accompanied by a number of side effects.
In addition, incomplete suppression of virus multiplication results in the development of so-called resistant viruses, against which drugs are no longer effective.
The work of experts from three institutes of the Academy of Sciences of the Czech Republic, the University of Technology in Prague and the University of Heidelberg opens the way to deal with the resistance of the virus.
They have shown that substances called metal-carborans act on the protein responsible for the multiplication of the HIV virus.
Metalcarbonates are compounds of boron, hydrogen, carbon, and cobalt.
These compounds block the spread of the virus differently than all the drugs used today, and therefore can overcome the problem of resistance.
In their work, scientists come up with new ‘improved’ compounds prepared on the basis of knowledge of the molecular mechanism of their binding to the viral protein.
Metal-carborans have a unique three-dimensional structure: two polyhedral cages made up of boron, hydrogen, and carbon atoms are connected by a metal atom, in this case cobalt.
Treacherous and resistant virus
HIV protease is a protein of the HIV virus that is essential for the life cycle of the virus.
Without HIV protease caused by HIV cleavage, no mature infectious virus particles would form.
When we stop HIV protease, we also stop the spread of the virus in the patient’s body, the researchers explain in a press release published by the Institute of Organic Chemistry and Biochemistry of the Academy of Sciences of the Czech Republic.
In a paper published in the Journal of Medicinal Chemistry, scientists describe a series of compounds in which two pairs of cages (see table) are connected by a short organic chain, which is further systematically altered.
Slightly weaker, but more reliable
The effect of this series of substances against HIV protease was tested in a test tube and also against its resistant (resistant) variants obtained from patients infected with HIV.
The effect of metallocarbonates on the common variant of the enzyme is not as strong as that of clinically used drugs, but it does not lose its effect for resistant variants against which the drugs used are often ineffective.
The unique mechanism of action, as well as their other properties such as biological and chemical stability, low toxicity and the possibility of further chemical treatments make metal carboranes interesting compounds for further research leading to the design of effective drugs against HIV, says Pavlína Řezáčová, head of the Structural Biology Laboratory of the Institute of Organic Chemistry and Biochemistry and the Institute of Molecular Genetics of the Academy of Sciences.
