The UN has outlined a plan to reduce emissions.
The UN-sponsored climate conference -- characterized by far-fetched attitudes and mutual defamation -- refocused on Friday on releasing a paper proposing ambitious reductions in greenhouse gases over the next 40 years with industrialized nations bearing most of the burden in the near term.
The text, which can provide a basis for a final political agreement on greenhouse gas regulation, highlights the remaining obstacles as well as illuminating the way forward.
But important progress has been seen in the negotiations that took place at the wrong time with more than 100 world leaders coming to Copenhagen next week.
Created by an ad hoc UN working group, this text unobtrusively outlines how much money rich countries should provide to the poor to deal with global warming in the short and long term.
And it provides a whole range of choices for key issues, including how to develop and manage emerging economies so they can reduce their carbon output and what the upper limit of global temperature rise that policymakers will still be able to tolerate should be.
This will give the process a great deal of flexibility, says John Coequyt, senior representative of the Washington Sierra Club.
Michael Zammit Cutajar, who designed the six-page paper, shorted the 180-page text from the negotiations to focus on what the top climate official at the UN, Yvo de Boer, described as a "big picture".
It outlines a possible agreement in which industrial nations could collectively reduce their emissions to 25 to 45 percent by the year compared to 1990 levels, while major developing countries could reduce their emissions to 15 to 30 percent during that period.
Together, the countries would reduce emissions by between 50 and 95 percent by 2050.
The European Union swiftly discussed a pledge on Friday to provide $3.6 trillion over the next three years to help poorer countries embrace adaptation to climate change -- from coping with floods and droughts to preventing deforestation.
Still, Friday listed the same kind of verbal fireworks that prevailed in talks last week.
U.S. Special Envoy for Climate Action Todd Stern rejected a speech demanding binding limits on greenhouse gas emissions for industrialized countries compared to volunteering for major emerging economies if they were not funded by the developed world.
The shift signaled that the Obama administration had established a tougher line towards China running officials of the Bush administration just two years ago.
The United States will not accede to the treaty without transferring major developing countries and carrying out actions, said Stern, who also complained that the text was not sufficient to secure restrictions and should be vetted by external observers.
Stern made the comment an hour after China’s deputy foreign minister He Yafei told the U.S. chief climate negotiator that either a lack of “common sense” or “extraordinary irresponsibility” led to a statement earlier in the week that the United States would not help China financially to deal with global warming.
With the future of the world’s major economic powers at stake, tensions have erupted both within the developing world and between the industrial world and emerging economies.
The current struggle is mostly for the preservation of individual economies rather than the preservation of the planet, between China and the United States to meet their respective commitments, while poorer nations point out that two dozen of the world's most influential countries are ignoring the scientific imperative to take stronger action.
Ricardo Ulate, a delegate to Costa Rica, said it was not surprising that major powers were fighting over who should bear the cost of curbing greenhouse gases, while vulnerable countries became much more aggressive in finding a way to prevent large emitters from being held accountable in their actions.
It’s clearly a game about the new economic hegemony developing, said Ulate, who also serves as a regional advisor on regional climate change in Mexico and Central America for international nature conservation.
Some of the countries most vulnerable to the effects of climate change indicated that they would like to continue pursuing a legally binding agreement in Copenhagen, but most of the main participants said that the best outcome of the talks would be a political agreement.
The Alliance of Small Island States, which has 43 members, created a 24-page draft agreement last Friday morning.
Artur Runge-Metzger, who led the international climate negotiations for the benefit of the European Commission, said that enforcement by small island nations has "triggered a political chokehold on the whole political process" partly because they are now united and demanding action from growing economies such as China and India.
The negotiations raised a new urgency once delegates focused on the fact that they had to resolve most of the remaining contentious issues before the heads of government could come to an agreement.
Senior officials such as India’s environment minister Jairam Ramesh and China’s deputy minister stepped out of the planes and ran through the halls of the Bella center to the closed doors of meetings and new conferences so they could set claims to be assessed next week.
