The UDF is raising the tone and calling on the Nouveau Centre party to no longer use their acronym.
The UDF, controlled by the MoDemFrancoise Bayrou party, responded on Friday to an attempt by the president of the Nouveau Centre party, Hervé Morin, to appropriate the abbreviation of the former Giscard party, saying that the abbreviation must not be used in any media under threat of prosecution.
Hervé Morin has publicly announced his intention to appropriate the abbreviation UDF, saying that Francois Bayrou does not deserve to carry her legacy after shaking hands with the left.
The Minister of Defence, whose party is a partner of the UMP, planned to confirm this strategy on Saturday before the National Council of the Nouveau Centre (NC).
This move gained support from MP Hervé de Charetta (former pro-UMP now for NC), who claims ownership of the UDF brand because he was the first to have it registered with the National Institute of Industrial Property (l'Institut national de la proprieté industrielle) in 2004.
But on Friday evening, a committee of the UDF run by friends of Francois Bayrou, who have no intention of being expropriated, stepped out of its silence and made a formal request to both the minister and MPs to stop using the acronym and hand back ownership of the trademark, under threat of criminal prosecution.
