While the court had to assess the merits of the action brought by Mrs Bettencourt-Meyers, the lawyers’ Friday court speech sometimes turned into a family hour of truth.
Liliana Bettencourt's lawyer submitted three letters sent by his client (in 1999, 2003 and 2005) to her notary in which she expressed her censure towards her husband Francoise Bettencourt-Meyers.
In a 2003 letter, Liliane Bettencourt added, “Could you explain to my daughter that I wrote to Banier once or twice a day for 15 years.
Ever since she got married, I've never been able to talk to Francoise."
The Nanterre Public Prosecutor’s Office found again that the applicant’s conduct was not justified, all the more so as the guardianship judge rejected her application to initiate proceedings to grant legal protection to her mother.
Liliane Bettencourt "is fully capable of attending court, not under protection or custody.
No one else will act for her,” said prosecutor Marie-Christine Daubigney.
The court eventually ruled that Mrs Bettencourt-Meyers's legitimacy would be upheld at the time the trial began.
The managerial revolution or the end of economic intelligence?
If nothing changes in the management of large French companies, our struggle for the development of economic intelligence has been futile...
For more than a decade, the behaviour of management of large companies towards employees has been reminiscent of the approach of companies towards consumers before the marketing revolution: the idea is for co-workers to identify with the "values" determined from above, as was the case before, when it was necessary to impose products on the consumer that came from the ideas of the heads of factory technicians.
By making the customer the center of business companies, the marketing revolution has aligned the strategy of conquering the market in the right direction... even though authoritarian efforts to impose products, different from customer preferences, regularly come back!
The passive attitude of employees can lead to fatal demoralization.
Suicides at France Telecom, PSA or Renault are just a visible part of a much more widespread general phenomenon, affecting mostly managerial cadres.
This demobilization adversely affects the development of all intellectual functions of society, including research and development, and more importantly, economic intelligence.
Indeed, the EI "requires an active approach and the ability to anticipate" from all stakeholders and requires commitments from employees that are completely at odds with the revenue of authoritarian management.
Therefore, we call for a managerial revolution that should aim to put employees at the center of the company’s interest as well as the client’s.
The relative usefulness of internal opinion polls.
Will internal opinion polls - as a questionnaire submitted to Orange employees - contribute to a revolution in management practices?
Unfortunately, I'm afraid not.
Mainly because I have already convinced myself that in the face of a new situation, the structure after various turns will return as a priority to what it has always done!
Furthermore, because authoritarianism, as one of the pathologies of power, increases in proportion to the severity of its own failures.
Finally, because most executives have a simplified view of human behavior.
Because they are graduate students for engineers, they have a mechanical interpretation of psychology.
For reasons of convenience of thought, they adopt an old behavioral theory, now revived by "neurosciences" from the USA and widely disseminated without much knowledge by scientific institutes and the media.
With the fact that it is possible to move the "leverages" (sic) of the involvement of managers, a recent survey by the agency Ipsos on the site Figaro.fr, which only confirms the managers in their position of mechanical control, unsuitable for today's world.
Identify and measure mobilization factors.
On the contrary, the managerial revolution necessary for the proper functioning of modern enterprises presupposes the adoption of a final vision of human behavior.
It consists in incorporating a basic insight into all management plans and practices: For employees, obligations to the company will only be possible if they appear to be a clear means of achieving their dreams, ambitions and projects.
Currently, this concept of employee motivation is dealt with only by the Motivational Functional Analysis studies.
These studies have shown that they evaluate their businesses on the basis of predetermined doxy, which will allow them, through the image that tells about the business, to evaluate what it offers them to achieve their life goals.
By identifying and measuring these mobilization factors, managers can control, anticipate, and anticipate their "social performance" and put their human resource management "on track."
This creates a fertile ground for the development of sound and efficient economic intelligence.
In a speech from Oslo, Obama earned praise from the right.
On Friday, the American right welcomed a speech delivered by Barack Obama the day before in Oslo, content with the fact that the 2009 Nobel Peace Prize winner advocated the concept of a "just war" against the enemies of the United States.
The conservatives, who initially scoffed at Obama's award on October 9, this time applauded the presidential speech, including Sarah Palin, a former vice presidential candidate in the 2008 election.
I liked what he said, Palin, the muse of the right-wing Republican wing, told USA Today, adding that she herself had commented on the "sometimes necessary" war in her memoirs, which are now being published.
War is, of course, the last thing Americans would want to have to do, but it is necessary.
All terrorists must be detained there, he believes.
President Obama, who inherited two wars in Afghanistan and Iraq from his predecessor George W. Bush, justified the deployment of forces in Oslo on Thursday and used the speech to clarify his decision to send an additional 30,000 troops to Afghanistan nine days before.
Another Obama opponent, Newt Gingrich, said the president had done a "very good job" in Oslo.
I think that the speech was really very good, congratulated the former Speaker of the House of Representatives, who especially appreciated the President's mention of "the existence of evil in the world".
In a way, I thought this speech was quite historic, Gingrich said during an interview on the radio show "The Takeaway".
The former MP, whom some consider a possible Republican candidate in the 2012 presidential election, was thrilled to see a "left-wing president" remind members of the Nobel Prize Committee "that they themselves would not be free and could not pass the Peace Prize if the use of force did not exist".
According to Michael Gerson, former speechwriter George W. Bush, now editor of the Washington Post, Obama delivered a "very American speech".
Not only did he introduce himself as a “world citizen” as he always did, but he “spoke like an American president” and reminded Europeans “that they live in a safe bubble that they didn’t create themselves, and that they’re not doing too much to preserve it,” Gerson said.
A few right-wing hawks include former U.N. Ambassador John Bolton, who described the speech as "uniform, pompous and uninspired", as stated on the National Review Online website.
To the left of the president, for example, Democratic Representative Dennis Kucinich is horrified at the sight of Barack Obama justifying the use of force.
"If we wrap the war in the cover of justice, we can easily justify the massacre of innocent people," he warned.
However, the mid-leftist press takes a laudable stance towards the president.
Although the Los Angeles Times continues to consider the awarding of the peace prize to Obama premature, it assessed his output as "overperformance" even for a speaker known for his talent.
The Oslo speech should serve as a guide to international decisions in conflict resolution, the fight against poverty and oppression," the California daily said.
Obama “speaked the speech that was needed,” the New York Times said, calling the speech “simple and instructive.”
Road hauliers: three marathons to an agreement that will save the supply of supplies for Christmas.
After three negotiating marathons, the road hauliers' union and the TLF, the only employers' organization left until the end, reached an agreement on Friday night that ended the call for a strike and the threat that hung over the supply of supplies for Christmas.
Dominique Bussereau, the secretary of state for transport, said Friday that he was “joyful” after several negotiations began on Wednesday morning.
After the second night of discussions, the negotiators broke up early on Friday with the hope that the text of the agreement would be signed as soon as possible at the end of the morning.
This is despite the fact that three employers’ organisations (FNTR, Unostra, OTRE) have withdrawn from the negotiations.
But it took more than six more hours for the meeting to begin at 11 a.m. for everyone to agree and for the agreement to be signed at 6 p.m.
This conflict "would hurt businesses greatly" and "would be in danger of disrupting the holidays at the end of the year," Bussereau said.
The text includes a wage increase of 4% for the lowest salaries (local and regional road transport) and 2.9% for the highest salaries (international transport).
The hourly wage at the lowest salary increases from 8.72 euros to 9.06.
It’s not much, but there’s a lot of effort behind it, explained Patrice Clos (FO).
Tonight, we will give orders to our members not to have any blockades, no blockades of supply centers.
But there may be a few more opponents who are not satisfied,” he added.
Philippe Grillot, the president of the TLF, welcomed the "right deal", although it was difficult to admit the increase in high salaries due to the international competition.
According to him, there will be an increase of 170 euros per month for the lowest wages and 100-120 euros for the highest ones.
It is an agreement of common sense and respect for employees, declared CMaxime Dumont (CFDT), while Thierry Douine (CFTC) welcomed the "historic agreement".
According to Richard Jaubert (CGT), this is an "acceptable compromise".
The agreement also foresees a 3% revaluation of travel expenses and a report on the state of play of road transport in the first half of 2010, which will also allow a focus on the 13th salary issue and the modernisation of the collective agreement.
Bussereau recalled the "100 million euro reduction in corporate payroll taxes" that was the subject of the government's amendment to the 2009 draft budget law, which was voted on Thursday night by the National Assembly.
The government will ask the Senate for a "consecutive" vote.
The signature allows this agreement to apply first to enterprises that are members of this organization, later to the entire field, in the case of expansion by the Ministry of Labour.
It will take place "as soon as possible", Bussereau assured.
The whole process can only be hindered by the opposition of employers' organizations.
The FNTR called the deal “bad” because “100 million euros has already been offered to the sector to offset part of the carbon tax.”
The Secretary of State for Transport forced us to take emergency action, not as a result of mutual analysis, but in order not to anger turkey eaters during the upcoming Christmas holidays, Unostra complained.
For Otre, the agreement threatens to “burie a large number of small and medium-sized enterprises in the industry” over the next 12 months.
RER A suburban trains: traffic interruptions on the weekend, unions dissatisfied with the proposals of the transport company RATP.
Interruptions on the RER A commuter train line, France’s largest public transport line, will continue over the weekend, as Friday’s negotiations between the unions and RATP’s management on the second day of the strike did not lead to any concrete results on the issue of the premium request.
On Saturdays and Sundays, i.e. the days of an important shopping weekend before Christmas, trains will run only between 10 am and 8 pm, on the main section (between La Défence and Nation) every second train will run, except for this section only one train out of four.
The connection to the SNCF will be cut off at Nanterre Préfecture, forcing passengers to switch trains.
The Galeries Lafayette department stores, which expect more than 200,000 customers every day, welcomed the fact that "the RATP sought to secure links with large department stores".
The RER A line runs from the west to the east of the Paris agglomeration.
The section managed by the RATP runs from Saint-Germain-en-Laye and Nanterre to Boissy-Saint-Léger and Marne-La-Vallée.
On Friday, one train out of two was in operation at rush hour, and virtually none of the trains were running at the off-peak time as planned.
As on Thursday, the residents of Ile de France arranged differently and there was no confusion on the platforms.
So early in the morning there were far fewer people at the Saint-Germain-en-Laye (Yvelines) station than usual, among other things because there were no pupils or students.
Jack Nbakina, an engineer, 29 from Boissy-Saint-Léger (Val-de-Marne) explained that he got up "an hour and a half early to make sure he arrived on time".
The Saint-Lazare railway station was not overcrowded, the SNCF said, as a larger number of bailiffs and law enforcement officers were forecasted.
The RER A commuter trains operated by SNCF in the direction from or to Cergy-Le-Haut arrived or departed from Saint-Lazare station with a connection to the metro.
Other general meetings of the strikers will be held on Saturday and Sunday, at which the results of Friday's afternoon meeting with the management, which the unions rated as "weak", will be evaluated.
The RER management proposes negotiations on a special protocol for RER A commuter trains in all respects, working time adjustment, career progression, etc.
However, this is not the case for drivers who demand a well-deserved premium, according to Thierry Garon (Southern Unions).
RATP even postponed the premium proposals for the time being, which scandalized the CGT, saying that the management "was not able to solve the problem, while for the travel carriers and SNCF it went".
At the new meeting, which is scheduled for Monday, "the conditions for the exercise of the profession will be reviewed more closely", RATP specified.
Which is why trade unionists think the business is "making fun of weekend travelers."
In the morning, about 150 drivers occupied the company committee at its Paris headquarters.
The leadership, which had so far rejected any discussion during the strike, therefore decided to hold a meeting in the interest of "calming down".
There is a risk that the conflict will spread to the RER B line on Tuesday, after Unsa and the Independents announce a strike alert.
The unions are asking for a premium of between 120 (Unsa) and 150 euros, including 30 euros of variables (CGT, FO, CFDT, Sud (South), Indépendants (Independent)) and are complaining about deteriorating working conditions on this line, which carries a million passengers a day.
RER commuter train drivers earn between 2,200 and 2,700 euros in gross wages and between 600 and 650 euros in bonuses for irregular working hours and for working on Sundays and holidays.
The Turkish judiciary has dissolved for the Kurdish side and this decision has serious consequences.
Turkey’s Constitutional Court ruled on Friday that the main pro-Kurdish party in the country should be abolished, prompting protests in the Kurdish community in the south-east of the country and in Istanbul.
This decision can greatly complicate the task of the government, which is trying to give the Kurdish community a friendly hand and try to end 25 years of conflict.
The party for a democratic society (DTP) has been dissolved because it has become "a nest of activities threatening the independence of the state and its indivisible unity," Supreme Court President Hasim Kilic told reporters after four days of negotiations.
The decision was taken unanimously by 11 judges when a majority of seven votes was needed to dissolve the party, Kili said, adding that 37 party cadres, including its president Ahmet Turk and MP Aysely Tugluk, were banned from participating in political life for five years.
The judge also announced the abolition of the parliamentary immunity enjoyed by Mr. Turk and Mrs. Tugluk and the confiscation of the party's assets by the Ministry of Finance.
The DTP party has 21 seats (out of 500) in Parliament.
The party's leadership warned before the verdict that MPs would rather leave Parliament than serve as non-political MPs.
The ruling is a continuation of a trial launched in 2007 by the prosecutor of the Court of Cassation Abdurrahman Yalcinkay, who accuses the DTP of obeying the "commands" of the Kurdistan Workers' Party (PKK), which Ankara and many countries consider a terrorist organization.
Many observers are convinced that the DTP is the legal political showcase of the rebels of the PKK.
The party assures that it has no "fundamental connection" with the PKK, but refuses to label it a terrorist organization and calls on the government to negotiate with it.
The verdict comes as the government hands the Kurdish community a friendly hand and offers a series of measures to strengthen their rights, attempting to curb Kurdish support for the PKK and end the conflict.
The DTP leadership has confirmed that the dissolution of the party could lead to renewed tensions in southeast Anatolia, where many demonstrations have degenerated in recent weeks against the conditions under which PKK leader Abdullah Ocalan is being held in clashes with police.
Since the announcement of the justice decision, thousands of protesters have gathered outside the DTP headquarters in Diyarbakir, a large city in the southeast that is populated mostly by Kurds.
Police used tear grenades and water cannons, while protesters threw Molotov cocktails or fired rocks from slingshots.
About a hundred people also demonstrated in Istanbul.
Following the verdict, Mr. Turk stated that the justice decision would only "deepen despair".
Turkey cannot resolve the issue by banning the party, he said in a press release.
The government, formed by the party that emerged from the Islamist movement, also condemned the decision.
We're against party interference on principle.
It doesn’t matter, Energy Minister Taner Yildiz said.
This decision is a complete blow to the democratic proposals launched by the government, political scientist Ahmet Insel commented.
Of course, we can expect a reaction from the PKK, he added.
On Thursday, the PKK claimed one of the deadliest attacks in northern Turkey, killing seven soldiers three days earlier.
