The Cradle of Dinosaurs
Tawa hallae looked like a lot of other carnivorous dinosaurs: An animal two meters long and 1.50 meters high ran on two strong hind limbs, had an elongated skull with sharp, curved teeth, short forelimbs with sickle claws and a long tail.
If this species lived a few million years later, there would be nothing extraordinary.
Sterling Nesbitt of the University of Texas at Austin and colleagues in Thursday's issue of the journal Science write that Tawa hallae was one of the first dinosaurs with these body features.
The animal lived about 215 million years ago in present-day New Mexico, which was then in the equatorial dry region of the supercontinent Pangaea.
Tawa opens a new window on the earlier evolution of dinosaurs, says Nesbitt.
It shows us a lot about kinship, distribution, and signs of early dinosaurs.
In 2006, Nesbitt and other paleontologists began excavations at Ghost Ranch in northern New Mexico.
Sometimes we found a dozen dinosaur bones in one day, unprecedented for Triassic deposits, says team member Randall Irmis of the Museum of Natural History in Utah.
Some of the bones were quickly identified by scientists as a new species.
During the excavations, the remains were collected from a total of five individuals.
The discovery confirms theories about the early history of dinosaurs.
The name "Tawa" comes from the sun god of the Hopi Indians.
For Sterling Nesbitt, this is an unusual finding: "The fossils of the Triassic dinosaurs are very rare, usually only individual fragments are found."
Other dinosaur experts do not share this enthusiasm unreservedly.
This finding is not particularly sensational, but it confirms some theories about the early history of dinosaurs, says Martin Sander of the University of Bonn.
According to the current scientific opinion, dinosaurs appeared for the first time about 230 million years ago.
However, many of the oldest fossils are not complete, so the assignment of pradinosaurs is mostly disputed.
Experts discuss, for example, when the lizards divided into three most important developmental lines: carnivorous theropods, which later included Tyrannosaurus rex, Velociraptor, and also birds, "long-necked" four-legged sauropods and their relatives, and herbivores Ornithischia (bird-birds), to which the species belonged for example.
Tawa hallae is the original terapod after an analysis by Nesbitt and his colleagues.
It has an interesting combination of primitive and advanced properties, Nesbitt says.
On the skull of Tawa hallae, for example, researchers found evidence of air sacs, which even the descendants of theropod birds have.
Thanks to the air sacs, the breathing of birds is more efficient than that of mammals.
In Tawa hallae, even the bones of the spine were apparently partially filled with air.
Tawa is the oldest and most primitive theropod with air sacs, says Randall Irmis.
Since the related lineage of the giant sauropods later also had air sacs and light bones, this useful innovation was probably already created by a common ancestor of the two groups.
At least three waves of migration to North America
Since the most primitive dinosaurs to date lived in South America, scientists have deduced that lizards first appeared there.
According to this, the three evolutionary lines split early and spread from South America to all continents, which at that time as the supercontinent Pangaea formed a unified Earth mass.
The team, along with Tawa Hallae, found the remains of two other, not particularly closely related theropods.
The three cannot be descended from the same common, immigrant ancestor, the researchers argue.
We believe there have been at least three waves of migration to North America, says Alan Turner of the American Museum of Natural History in New York, co-author of the scientific study.
Of course, there are also contradictions.
One even older species, Silesaurus, which belongs to the group of the heaviest dinosaurs, lived in today's Poland, says Bonno paleontologist Martin Sander.
His conjecture could put together a distorted picture, as very many primitive dinosaur fossils have been preserved in South America, while they are rarely found on other continents.
How the dinosaurs proved that they evolved from a relatively rare by-line of reptiles to the ruling vertebrates on earth in the time of the Earth's Middle Ages remains a puzzle.
During the Triassic, dinosaurs shared their living space with many other reptiles, such as the ancestors of today's crocodiles and flying lizards and countless other lizards.
Towards the end of the Triassic, dinosaurs spread throughout the world and many new species developed, while relatives became extinct and the interface of the Triassic and Jurassic.
The success story didn’t last forever.
There are two hypotheses to explain this change, says Martin Sander.
There may have been a mass extinction that dinosaurs accidentally survived, but reptiles did not.
Or the dinosaurs adapted better, so they could squeeze out the competition.
In any case, the success story did not last forever.
150 million years later, a meteorite impact helped another group of animals, which also evolved in the Triassic and have lived in the shade ever since: mammals.
Solidarity from Vienna to Sao Paulo
The list is long and the signatories are international.
The list includes professors from the University of Toronto, the University of Cambridge, the University of Vienna or Berkeley, California.
Associate professors from Naples, Quebec, Edinburgh, New York, Sao Paulo, Berlin or Bremen joined.
The police eviction of the occupied Goethe University casino in Frankfurt has caused a worldwide stir.
278 professors and lecturers at Goethe University, as well as universities across Germany, Europe and North and South America, stand in solidarity with the protesting students at the Westend campus.
In a statement written in German and English, they "disapprove" of the Presidium's incited police intervention.
Because the walls were scribbled and the artworks were done, university president Werner M?ller-Estler had the building occupied last week by striking students and lecturers.
Five students were injured.
The damage to the cause, the signers judge, does not justify "the violent dissolution of the self-organized teaching of students and teachers by the police commando".
The eviction represents an "unacceptable interference" with the freedoms of research and science.
The exclusive focus on vandalism serves to "unauthorize and criminalize protest" and divert attention away from content.
The Presidium avoided the necessary discussion.
Speakers call for an end to criminal prosecution.
It is claimed that the majority of strikers did not support material damage.
Legitimate protest
The youth of the Verdi trade union and the German trade union also stand in solidarity with the students.
The protest is a legitimate expression of growing concern for one’s own future, says the enigmatic Land Youth Verdi Alexander Klein.
Meanwhile, Hessen Science Minister Eva Kuehne-Hurmann (CDU) is defending the university president and the police.
I am grateful to the university president.
Destruction and occupation are totally unacceptable means, she said Thursday in the Aktuellen Stunde (Current Hour) in the Wiesbaden Landtag.
We have sympathy for the protest, but we have no sympathy for vandalism, said CDU MP Peter Beuth.
The opposition factions of the SPD, the Greens and Linke saw it differently.
