New Silicon - Valley
For many years it was a secret city, inaccessible to visitors from the west.
Zelenograd, one of the ten districts of the capital of Moscow, in the Soviet Union was a strictly guarded location where secret weapons research was carried out.
Today, this district with 216,000 inhabitants, located 37 kilometers from the center of Moscow, is considered the "Russian Silicon Valley".
Important micro- and nanoelectronic research and production centres are located here.
Since September 2008, representatives of Zelenograd have established contacts with the Frankfurt-based Riedberg Science Centre - with university institutions and companies of the Frankfurt Innovation Centre (FIZ).
A number of mutual visits took place and on Wednesday, Zelenograd and Ridberg signed a "Protocol on Close Cooperation" in Frankfurt.
The Russian delegation was led by Moscow’s vice-mayor Yuri Rosljak and Zelenograd prefect Anatoly Smirnov, while Frankfurt was signed by senior planning officer Edwin Schwarz.
In 2010, representatives of FIZ and small and medium-sized enterprises engaged in natural science research will go to a seminar in Zelenograd.
Scientific exchange
This is an ongoing scientific exchange.
It is also about economic relations.
FIZ companies will be able to take a foothold in the growing Russian market.
On the other hand, Russian scientific companies want to get contracts in Germany.
Zelenograd is home to major Russian research institutes and companies.
These include the Moscow Institute of Electron Technology, large concerns Sitronics and Rossiyskaya Elektronika.
The district was established in 1958 as a so-called "socialist planned city" for arms research.
Zelenograd (literally "Green City") got its name from the wooded hilly landscape into which the research facilities are planted.
The Stuttgart Brake
The Stuttgart 21 dimension cannot be prepared at all.
For the supporters of the project, it is quite simply the "new heart of Europe".
S21 is more than the launch of a railway station, more than a monstrous building that plunges the capital of Baden-Wuerttemberg into a decade of desperate building chaos.
Stuttgart 21 was born out of the spirit of the 1980s.
Head stations with tracks that ended in the city centre were then considered 19th century transport and technical fossils that act as brakes on modern rail transport, as it took an enormous amount of time to rear-end the locomotives.
Drive, stop for a while, go on - that's how it should work.
And that's why the head stations are disappearing: in Frankfurt and Munich.
And in Stuttgart: the transit station, which lies roughly halfway along the trans-European railway route between Paris and Budapest/Bratislava - hence the slogan of "the heart of Europe".
It really starts with the S21, although visions from the 80s are no longer compatible with reality.
The very ambitious designers themselves recognized that in the Hessian and Bavarian cities, the start of construction is almost unfinanceable.
Since there are modern shuttle trains with motor and control vehicles at both ends, head stations no longer have problems with detours and exits.
Still: Stuttgart 21 starts, including the new ICE line to Ulm.
This was done by local and local politicians.
The railways cooperate, also because the risks of the largest individual infrastructure project in the republic are borne by the taxpayer and not by the state concern.
Urbanistically, the project can still be justified.
A new urban space will be created, which - if we believe the computer images of designers - will contain a lot of greenery.
For the railway transport system, the S21 is harmful.
The transit station and the construction of the line are designed for passenger transport, which - typically in the 1980s - was attributed to a huge increase.
There was no competition for cheap flights.
However, modern transport policy must first of all be about strengthening freight transport, because rail transport is far more environmentally friendly than road freight cars.
But the new track is not suitable for freight trains due to steep climbs.
Even more serious is that S21 indirectly affects many other railway projects.
A good six billion euros were to be buried in Swabia.
That's the official number.
Experts consider the real 10 to 15 billion.
It is clear that in the next decade there will be a lack of funding for other nodes and bottlenecks in the network.
There are sixty major projects on the list of the Ministry of Transport.
One of the most important is the construction of a roughly 180 km long route through the Rhine valley.
Since 1987, it has been built at a slow pace on this route.
You need to push hard here.
But the S21 will be like a brake.
The line through the Rhine Valley will become a bottle of international freight: right in the heart of Europe.
