Worlds of Dreams
Some see images and hear voices that others do not see or hear.
It is not only the mentally ill or in drug intoxication that draw the line between imagination and reality.
As long as it happens in your sleep, everything is fine.
If we lie with our eyes closed in our dark room, we may surround ourselves with wildest fantasies and fanciful mirages.
However, those who experience dream states in their waking life, see and hear things that others do not see and hear, pay mostly for a fool or a drug addict, or at least as a weirdo in today’s Western world.
However, such images and voices do not arise only in the mentally ill or in drug intoxication.
Our imagination is to blame: The same neural processes that allow us to design houses, paint paintings, or write novels will now and then ensure that the boundaries between dream, imagination, and reality merge.
Dreams altered state of consciousness can occur in various forms, at best we call them visions, at worst delusions.
Although the initiator and the effect may vary, however, the visions of the mystic Hildegard von Bingen, the drug experiences of the New-Age prophet Carlos Castaneda, shamanic states of delusion, psychosis, and hallucinations can be inferred from similar processes.
Hallucinations or visions occur when the balance of the brain's neuronal transmitters - primarily dopamine, noradrenaline, serotonin, and acetylcholine - is derailed and the interaction between the different parts of the brain is disrupted.
Complex hallucinations and delusional thoughts occur very often in schizophrenic psychosis.
Gravity has no power over it.
The connection between delusion and dream has occupied philosophers and physicians since ancient times.
Aristotle understood hallucinations as a form of dream in the waking state, Wilhelm Griesinger, one of the founders of modern psychology, stated in 1861 "a great similarity of delusion with dream states", for Sigmund Freud the dream was even "psychosis, with all nonsense, delusions, delusions of the senses".
It's fall 2001, Henning T. turns into a comic book character.
His body is two-dimensional and vividly colored.
Gravity has no power over it, hovering at the ceiling of the room.
He's feeling a kick.
Behind him are winged devilish figures with bloody red grimaces, valuing their teeth.
They chase him, kick him with heavy, fiery shoes, throw him against the wall, feel pain all over his body.
Loud, evil voices threaten from the walls and from the radio.
He can no longer tolerate voices that insult and insult him.
Henning T. pulls two cables from the stereo, knotting them into a loop and fixing it to a hook on the ceiling.
He stands on one speaker and puts a loop around his neck.
He jumps.
Looping's on.
Learn, chorusing voices tearing his drum, "go to the clinic and get treated!"
Today Henningu T. 40 years old, experienced six acute psychoses, the last 2 years ago, the first almost 20 years ago.
LSD was triggered.
His diagnosis is schizoaffective paranoid psychosis, besides, he is manic-depressive, taking drugs against depression, mania, schizophrenia.
He learned to live with his illness, he was married for three years.
In psychosis, I experienced the worst fear and the deepest doubt, he says.
Ghosts are a terrible reality.
About 1% of people get schizophrenia at least once in their lives, and in psychiatric clinics it is the second most frequently treated disease after depression.
In acute schizophrenic psychosis, most sufferers can no longer distinguish between the inner and outer worlds, they get into an overexcited state that can lead to hallucinations, size, relationship illusions or the illusion of persecution.
Especially widespread is the hearing of voices - voices that command, comment or conduct dialogues.
Even optical hallucinations are not uncommon.
The affected person is not able to distinguish the important from the unimportant, the brain can not filter out the disturbing signals, consciousness is flooded with impressions.
Like a dream, psychosis opens up a flood of thoughts and fantasies that come from the deepest layers of consciousness.
The perception of reality in psychosis is subject-centered, says Professor Thomas Fuchs, chief physician of the General Psychiatry Clinic at the University of Heidelberg.
The schizophrenic is at the center of the action, everything has a meaning directed at him.
At the same time, he gets into a passive role, becoming, like in a dream, overwhelmed by events and unable to actively shape them.
Therefore, schizophrenics often feel threatened, controlled, and manipulated.
Comparison with reality is usually not possible, ghosts are a terrible reality, awakening is excluded.
Once in a lifetime to experience hallucinations
Unlike in a dream, Fuchs says, "the sensory and spatial structure of reality, which one perceives in psychosis, remains fundamentally preserved."
Misguided thoughts and hallucinations are based on reality, the alienation of the experience takes place in a real framework.
Scientists are still puzzled as to why our brains do such things.
Exceptional states can lead anyone to lose touch with reality in the short term, Fuchs says.
But not everyone develops into a psychosis.
There seems to be a genetic predisposition to schizophrenia, but studies on twins have shown that genes are not the only determining factor.
Scientists believe that the affected people have minimal brain damage.
We believe that early-stage neuronal brain maturation, such as maternal viral disease, will be damaged during pregnancy, Fuchs explains.
However, it remains a riddle how the neuronal system malfunctions, which did not manifest itself in any way for many years.
Influences of the environment also play a role - stress or traumatic experiences can be the initiator of psychosis, if there is a disposition to it.
Also, hallucinogenic drugs can trigger psychosis because they interfere with the transmission system.
When our brain gets wet
The crazy thing is that psychotronics suffer from their hallucinations, and in order to get rid of them, they swallow expensive drugs, others give money for drugs to get them, says psychology professor Erich Kasten from Lubeck.
Whether we perceive delusions as pleasant or unpleasant is often just a matter of attitude.
Kasten has been collecting reports of hallucinations and delusions for ten years, last year he interpreted his results in the book "Die irreale Welt in unserem Kopf" (The unreal world in our head).
Hallucinations belong to the typical accompanying phenomena of psychoses, but also to surprisingly many other diseases.
In addition to mental disorders such as borderline personality disorder or depression, diseases such as migraine, epilepsy, multiple sclerosis or Alzheimer’s or brain trauma are also common.
Surprisingly, under certain conditions, even the brain of a healthy person hallucinates.
Hallucinations, according to Kasten, consist of the contents of thoughts that are normally suppressed.
They arise when the parts of the brain in which sensory perception is processed are too active or too little suppressed; when our brain boils, or when there is no stimulation.
Drugs can trigger this condition just like brain damage or psychosis.
But also the withdrawal of stimuli, stress, worries with love or other states of emergency.
In more recent studies, up to a third of those surveyed reported having experienced a hallucination at least once in their lives.
In the summer of 2005, Sarah K. is 16 years old, lives in a small town in Mecklenburg-Vorpommern and attends the local grammar school.
A perfectly normal girl, actually.
If it weren't for the shapes and voices.
During breaks, she may be approached by a collapsible woman with long, dark hair.
When she answers, her classmates look at her with surprise - no one but her sees and hears this boy.
This shy girl considers herself an uptight dreamer, but Sarah K. does not dream, she knows that.
He is awake, he hears and sees the boy, just as he hears and sees the girl sitting next to him in the bench.
He can even feel his presence, at least for a few moments.
It's a nice feeling, she likes the boy.
Am I crazy? he asks.
But he knows that this boy and other delusions are not real and will disappear again.
At night, the signs are rather discouraging.
Often, delusions are a burden.
When she is sitting in the classroom, she cannot watch the lessons many times, because the teacher in her eyes and ears is just introducing a new classmate, but he explains to everyone else audible and visible on the board of mathematical equations.
At night, the appearances are rather discouraging.
When she is waiting in her dark room for a sleep that comes rarely and too late, she cannot often tell whether she is awake or already asleep, whether the images she sees, grimaces, or a girl with bleeding cuts on her arms and legs arise before her eyes open or closed.
Leave me alone, he's yelling at the characters.
She doesn't tell her parents and friends about it, they'd think she was crazy.
Autumn 2009. Sarah K. is 20 years old today.
She graduated high school last year and lives with her boyfriend.
A year ago, the hallucinations stopped.
Since she contacted psychologist Kasten on the Internet, she knows exactly that she has not gone crazy.
Delusions are also an art of despair.
If someone is socially isolated or deprived of stimuli, they are likely to have hallucinations, Kasten says.
My guess is that the brain doesn’t have enough work and takes care of its own entertainment.
Sarah K., an only child, was afraid of other children as a little girl, often playing alone.
Her hallucinations began when she learned at age 13 that the man she calls dad since she thinks he is not her own father.
Because visual and acoustic hallucinations involve the same brain regions that also process real perceptions and sounds, it is difficult for people like Sarah K. to distinguish between delusions and reality.
Hallucinations are also images that the brain lets form, which is why they seem so real."
Kasten also interprets night dreams as a form of hallucination.
Hallucinations in healthy people are not fundamentally different from hallucinations in acute psychosis.
Unlike schizophrenics, mentally healthy people are able to identify their delusions as unrealistic.
Kasten therefore advises his patients to rate hallucinations as an extraordinary ability.
Borderline between Dream and Hallucination
Unfortunately, in our over-concentrated world, the imaginary experience is mostly pathological, says Michael Schmidt-Degenhard, professor in Heidelberg and chief physician of the Psychiatric and Psychotherapeutic Clinic at the Florence-Nightingale Hospital in Dusseldorf.
Psychosis is a severe, agonizing disease, but it also brings positives, creativity - a mirage is also an art of despair.
Schmidt-Degenhard investigated the so-called oneiroid form of experiences, a special form of altered consciousness to dream.
Oneiroid states are highly complex, detailed fictional dreams that the subject considers to be real and cannot even distinguish them retroactively from the waking state.
The oneiroid state of consciousness arises in extreme situations caused by trauma or disease, for example, patients with polyradicular inflammation who experience full-consciousness motor paralysis.
When a person is threatened by the loss of the world and of himself, even if he is completely unable to move, he replaces life-threatening real situations with his own imaginary world, which is disconnected from reality, says Schmidt-Degenhard.
A type of borderline between a dream and a hallucination.
Since it is not possible to manage a situation in reality, the worlds will change, but the real situation will become present in the imagination.
An intense form of sensory support and sensory transfer in an intolerable situation that allows us humans to form our own ability to pass into a loss of consciousness in an instant.
Everything is real, even later in memories
Art historian Peter Cornelius Claussen also describes his oneiroid experiences in his book "Herzwechsel" (The Exchange of Hearts) as a soul rescue action.
He was 49 years old when, after heart valve surgery followed by a heart transplant, his consciousness set out on a multi-day journey, with his body lying motionless in the intensive care unit.
Claussen plunges into a world he has created, visiting strange times and places: He becomes an old man bedridden, in a train sanatorium, a robot watches over his health.
He lives in the early Middle Ages among the nobility, which produces narcotic substances from blood.
He is kidnapped by a Greek man on a motorcycle, surfs the firn in the Alps on a hospital bed, and meets a Korean mobster.
Immerse yourself completely in the imaginary, everything is real, even later in memories.
For Claussen, these inner paths are fundamentally different from any dream.
A dream is a different state, it describes its experience.
Contrary to dreams, the memories of those mental journeys are still clear years later and in unimportant details.
Even brighter and more intense than the actual experience.
