75% of working mothers have work-related problems.
Discrimination in the workplace has increased in recent years, especially among younger women who intend to have a child.
This is the result of a study 'The Fertility and Career of Spanish Women' conducted by CSIC in collaboration with the Women's Institute.
The study involved 9,737 women between the ages of 15 and 75, and the results are clear: 75% of working mothers have limited opportunities in the labor market because of motherhood.
The study highlights that at the beginning of cohabitation, there are many differences in opinion on the number of children, depending on whether they work or not, as well as on the type of employment.
Women who do not work outside the home, work part-time or do not have a stable job, begin to live with their partner earlier, give birth to their first child earlier, and have more children overall.
On the other hand, women with stable employment, especially in the public sector, postpone cohabitation and motherhood, and have fewer descendants.
"Women aged 35 to 49 with stable employment have their first child for an average of 3.7 years from the start of cohabitation. This figure is 4.1 for women who have devoted most of their lives to achieving stable employment and therefore had to postpone cohabitation and the arrival of children.
The type of occupation also has a strong influence on motherhood, although it has less influence on the time of commencing cohabitation with a partner,” explains Margarita Delgado, who is engaged in research at CSIC.
Another factor affecting the age of women at the time of marriage andbirth of a child is the degree of education.
Research shows that the higher the level of education, the higher the age when women get married and have their first child.
There are also differences between women of the same generation.
For example, in the 35 to 49 age group, women with primary and higher education gave birth to their first child at the age of 25.1 and 32.1 respectively.
“There is another difference between women depending on their level of education.
Women with primary education get married and give birth to their first child before they find a stable job, while women with secondary or higher education prefer to get a stable job before marriage and the birth of their first child,” says Delgado.
