The auxiliary system for the handbrake is already mandatory.
As in the case of the ABS anti-lock braking system, it will also be with ESP stability control, auxiliary handbrake systems, all this will become mandatory equipment of European cars.
In fact, it is already part of the mandatory equipment for all newly registered passenger cars and light commercial vehicles, while for others a deadline is set for eliminating the shortage, which is February 2011.
The measure put in place in the EU aims to increase pedestrian protection, while working to help prevent many collisions.
The auxiliary handbrake system increases the pressure on the brakes in an emergency, which the system detects when the driver presses.
However, it is not always possible to maintain this pressure until the end.
According to a study conducted by car parts manufacturer Bosch, a third of drivers who have an accident did not press the brake before the collision, and half of them did not use the full force of the brake.
Up to 1,100 accidents
On the contrary, this assistance requires the maximum from the braking system, shortening the braking distance of the vehicle.
According to a study conducted in the EU alone, if all vehicles were equipped with this type of equipment, up to 1,100 pedestrian-related fatalities could be avoided annually.
Reducing this number will be even more striking - according to calculations, one in four accidents would be avoided with an impact on people - after the introduction of so-called intelligent handbrake systems.
In this case, the vehicles will be equipped with a system that (using radar or camera) captures obstacles and reports them to the driver, in addition to light braking.
If the driver responds, it will help him increase the pressure on the pedal if necessary.
If the driver does not react, even if the collision cannot be prevented, the device will affect the brake as much as possible and reduce the risk of damage to a minimum.
